		<profileDesc>
			<abstract>
				<p>Motivated by the findings of modular structure in the association cortex, we study a multi-modular model of associative memory that can successfully store memory patterns with different levels of activity. We show that the segregation of synaptic conductances into intra-modular linear and inter-modular nonlinear ones considerably enhances the network&apos;s memory retrieval performance. Compared with the conventional, single-module associative memory network, the multi-modular network has two main advantages: It is less susceptible to damage to columnar input, and its response is consistent with the cognitive data pertaining to category specific impairment.</p>
			</abstract>
